# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-kriol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] The **2021 Australian census**, simply called the **2021 Census**, was the eighteenth national Census of Population and Housing in Australia.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] The 2021 Census took place on 10 August 2021, and was conducted by the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS).
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] It had a response rate of 96.1%, up from the 95.1% at the 2016 census.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] The total population of the Commonwealth of Australia was counted as 25,422,788, an increase of 8.6 per cent or 2,020,896 people over the previous 2016 census.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] Results from the 2021 census were released to the public on 28 June 2022 from the Australian Bureau of Statistics website.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] A small amount of additional 2021 census data was released in October 2022 and in 2023.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] Australia's next census is scheduled to take place in 2026.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] The census was undertaken during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] It therefore provided a clear snapshot of how the pandemic impacted Australian society.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] In Australia, completing the census is compulsory for all people in Australia on census night, only excluding foreign diplomats and their families.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] Census data is used to "help governments, businesses, not-for-profit and community organisations across the country make informed decisions", including helping governments to plan the provision of services.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] An independent report from Lateral Economics found that for every $1 of investment on the census, $6 of benefits are created in the Australian economy.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] Since the 2001 Census, all households have the option of allowing their census data, including personal information such as names and addresses, to be stored by the National Archives of Australia (NAA) for 99 years.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] 99 years after Census Night, the NAA will release that data to the public in a Census Time Capsule.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] Censuses stored by the NAA cannot by accessed, amended, or retrieved by anyone, including courts and tribunal, until their release, the first of which will occur in 2100.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] The 2020 Census Test occurred on 27 October 2020 with around 100,000 households from Sydney, Adelaide, Darwin, and Canberra, as well as communities in Karratha, Warrnambool, and Alice Springs Town Camps.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] Every census, the ABS makes a recommendation to the Australian Government on the topics to be included, based on the benefit that data would provide to Australia.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] Through the *Census and Statistics Amendment (Statistical Information) Regulations 2020*, the federal parliament approves topics that may be included.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] For the 2021 census, the ABS had been authorised to include questions relating to long-term health conditions and service in the Australian Defence Force, and would not continue asking questions about home internet access considering the rise of mobile devices.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] This represented the first significant change to census topics since 2006.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] Through late 2017, the ABS began discussions with major census data users on what was needed.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] From 3 April to 30 June 2018, a formal consultation process occurred on the online "ABS Consultation Hub", with the ABS receiving 450 submissions, 315 of which were published with consent.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] Since 2006, the ABS has allowed the census to be completed online, moving in 2016 to be digital-first.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] Like 2016, the 2021 Census was primarily collected online, with paper census forms being available on request for any household.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] In 2016, around a third of all households requested and completed their census using the paper form.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] The population counts for Australian states and territories were that New South Wales remains the most populous state, with 8,072,163 people counted, ahead of Victoria (6,503,491) and Queensland (5,156,138).
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] Of all residents over two-thirds (72.4% or 18,235,690) were born in Australia.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] Over a quarter of the population (27.6% or 7,502,450 persons) said they were born overseas.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] After Australia, England is the most common birthplace with 927,490 people.
[src:australian-kriol/2021-australian-census] India became the third-largest country of birth, surpassing China and New Zealand.
[src:australian-kriol/a] It is similar in shape to the Ancient Greek letter alpha, from which it derives.
[src:australian-kriol/a] The uppercase version consists of the two slanting sides of a triangle, crossed in the middle by a horizontal bar.
[src:australian-kriol/a] The lowercase version is often written in one of two forms: the double-storey |a| and single-storey |ɑ|.
[src:australian-kriol/a] The latter form is commonly used in handwriting and fonts based on it, especially fonts intended to be read by children, and is also found in italic type.
[src:australian-kriol/a] In English, the name of the letter is the *long A* sound, pronounced /ˈeɪ/.
[src:australian-kriol/a] Its name in most other languages matches the letter's pronunciation in open syllables.
[src:australian-kriol/a] The earliest known ancestor of A is *aleph*—the first letter of the Phoenician alphabet—where it represented a glottal stop [ʔ], as Phoenician only used consonantal letters.
[src:australian-kriol/a] In turn, the ancestor of aleph may have been a pictogram of an ox head in proto-Sinaitic script influenced by Egyptian hieroglyphs, styled as a triangular head with two horns extended.
[src:australian-kriol/a] When the ancient Greeks adopted the alphabet, they had no use for a letter representing a glottal stop—so they adapted the sign to represent the vowel /a/, calling the letter by the similar name *alpha*.
[src:australian-kriol/a] In the earliest Greek inscriptions dating to the 8th century BC following the Greek Dark Ages, the letter rests upon its side.
[src:australian-kriol/a] However, in the later Greek alphabet it generally resembles the modern capital form—though many local varieties can be distinguished by the shortening of one leg, or by the angle at which the cross line is set.
[src:australian-kriol/a] The Etruscans brought the Greek alphabet to the Italian Peninsula, and they left the form of alpha unchanged.
[src:australian-kriol/a] When the Romans adopted the Etruscan alphabet to write Latin, the resulting form used in the Latin script would come to be used to write many other languages, including English.
[src:australian-kriol/a] During Roman times, there were many variant forms of the letter A.
[src:australian-kriol/a] First was the monumental or lapidary style, which was used when inscribing on stone or other more permanent media.
[src:australian-kriol/a] There was also a cursive style used for everyday or utilitarian writing, which was done on more perishable surfaces.
[src:australian-kriol/a] Due to the perishable nature of these surfaces, there are not as many examples of this style as there are of the monumental, but there are still many surviving examples of different types of cursive, such as majuscule cursive, minuscule cursive, and semi-cursive minuscule.
[src:australian-kriol/a] Variants also existed that were intermediate between the monumental and cursive styles.
[src:australian-kriol/a] The known variants include the early semi-uncial (c.
[src:australian-kriol/a] 4th–8th centuries), and the late semi-uncial (c.
[src:australian-kriol/a] At the end of the Roman Empire (5th century CE), several variants of the cursive minuscule developed through Western Europe.
[src:australian-kriol/a] Among these were the semi-cursive minuscule of Italy, the Merovingian script in France, the Visigothic script in Spain, and the Insular or Anglo-Irish semi-uncial or Anglo-Saxon majuscule of Great Britain.
[src:australian-kriol/a] By the ninth century, the Caroline script, which was very similar to the present-day form, was the principal form used in book-making, before the advent of the printing press.
[src:australian-kriol/a] This form was derived through a combining of prior forms.
[src:australian-kriol/a] 15th-century Italy saw the formation of the two main variants that are known today.
[src:australian-kriol/a] These variants, the *Italic* and *Roman* forms, were derived from the Caroline Script version.
[src:australian-kriol/a] The Italic form ⟨ɑ⟩, also called *script a*, is often used in handwriting; it consists of a circle with a vertical stroke on its right.
[src:australian-kriol/a] In the hands of medieval Irish and English writers, this form gradually developed from a 5th-century form resembling the Greek letter tau ⟨τ⟩.
[src:australian-kriol/a] The Roman form ⟨a⟩ is found in most printed material, and consists of a small loop with an arc over it.
[src:australian-kriol/a] Both derive from the majuscule form ⟨A⟩.
[src:australian-kriol/a] In Greek handwriting, it was common to join the left leg and horizontal stroke into a single loop, as demonstrated by the uncial version shown.
[src:australian-kriol/a] Many fonts then made the right leg vertical.
[src:australian-kriol/a] In some of these, the serif that began the right leg stroke developed into an arc, resulting in the printed form, while in others it was dropped, resulting in the modern handwritten form.
[src:australian-kriol/a] Graphic designers refer to the *Italic* and *Roman* forms as *single-decker a* and *double decker a* respectively.
[src:australian-kriol/a] Italic type is commonly used to mark emphasis or more generally to distinguish one part of a text from the rest set in Roman type.
[src:australian-kriol/a] There are some other cases aside from italic type where *script a* ⟨ɑ⟩, also called *Latin alpha*, is used in contrast with Latin ⟨a⟩, such as in the International Phonetic Alphabet.
[src:australian-kriol/a] In English, ⟨a⟩ is the indefinite article (with the alternative form *an* when followed by a vowel).
[src:australian-kriol/a] The double ⟨aa⟩ sequence does not occur in native English words, but is found in some words derived from foreign languages such as *Aaron* and *aardvark*.
[src:australian-kriol/a] However, ⟨a⟩ occurs in many common digraphs, all with their own sound or sounds, particularly ⟨ai⟩, ⟨au⟩, ⟨aw⟩, ⟨ay⟩, ⟨ea⟩ and ⟨oa⟩.
[src:australian-kriol/a] In most languages that use the Latin alphabet, ⟨a⟩ denotes an open unrounded vowel, such as /a/, /ä/, or /ɑ/.
[src:australian-kriol/a] An exception is Saanich, in which ⟨a⟩—and the glyph ⟨Á⟩—stands for a close-mid front unrounded vowel /e/.
[src:australian-kriol/a] The Latin letters ⟨A⟩ and ⟨a⟩ have Unicode encodings U+0041 A LATIN CAPITAL LETTER A and U+0061 a LATIN SMALL LETTER A.
[src:australian-kriol/a] These are the same code points as those used in ASCII and ISO 8859.
[src:australian-kriol/a] There are also precomposed character encodings for ⟨A⟩ and ⟨a⟩ with diacritics, for most of those listed above; the remainder are produced using combining diacritics.
[src:australian-kriol/a] Variant forms of the letter have unique code points for specialist use: the alphanumeric symbols set in mathematics and science, Latin alpha in linguistics, and halfwidth and fullwidth forms for legacy CJK font compatibility.
[src:australian-kriol/a] The Cyrillic and Greek homoglyphs of the Latin ⟨A⟩ have separate encodings U+0410 А CYRILLIC CAPITAL LETTER A and U+0391 Α GREEK CAPITAL LETTER ALPHA.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] ABC began in 1943 as the NBC Blue Network, a radio network that was spun off from NBC, as ordered by the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) in 1942.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] The reason for the order was to expand competition in radio broadcasting in the United States, specifically news and political broadcasting, and broaden the projected points of view.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Only a few companies, such as NBC and CBS, dominated the radio market.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] NBC conducted the split voluntarily in case its appeal of the ruling was denied, and it was forced to split its two networks into separate companies.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Regular television news broadcasts on ABC began soon after the network signed on its initial owned-and-operated television station (WJZ-TV, now WABC-TV) and production center in New York City in August 1948.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Broadcasts continued as the ABC network expanded nationwide.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Until the early 1970s, ABC News programs and ABC in general consistently ranked third in viewership behind CBS and NBC news programs.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] ABC had fewer affiliate stations and a weaker prime-time programming slate to support the network's news operations compared to the two larger networks, each of which had established their radio news operations during the 1930s.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] By the 1970s, the network had effectively turned around, with its prime-time entertainment programs achieving more substantial ratings and drawing in higher advertising revenue and profits for ABC overall.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] With the appointment of the president of ABC Sports, Roone Arledge as president of ABC News in 1977, ABC invested the resources to make it a significant source of news content.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Arledge, known for experimenting with the broadcast "model", created many of ABC News' most popular and enduring programs, including *20/20*, *World News Tonight*, *This Week*, *Nightline*, and *Primetime Live*.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] In June 1998, ABC News (which owned an 80% stake in the service), Nine Network and ITN sold their respective interests in Worldwide Television News to the Associated Press.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Additionally, ABC News signed a multi-year content deal with AP for its affiliate video service, Associated Press Television News (APTV), while providing material from ABC's news video service, ABC News One, to APTV.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Scandal erupted on October 7, 1985, over a decision by Arledge, president of ABC News and Sports, to kill a 13-minute report about Marilyn Monroe, possibly due to his close ties to Ethel Kennedy.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] *20/20* drew criticism from the program's co-anchors, Hugh Downs and Barbara Walters, and the executive producer, Av Westin.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Arledge said that he had killed the piece because it was "gossip-column stuff" and "does not live up to its billing." Downs, however, took issue with Arledge's judgment.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] "I am upset about the way it was handled," he said in an interview.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] "I honestly believe that this is more carefully documented than anything any network did during Watergate.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] I lament the fact that the decision reflects badly on people I respect and it reflects badly on me and the broadcast." Additionally, Westin said: "I don't anticipate not putting it on the air.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] We are documenting that there was a relationship between Bobby and Marilyn and Jack and Marilyn.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Fred Otash, a detective who said he was the chief wiretapper, is interviewed on camera, and ABC staff members said three other wiretappers corroborated his account.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] In addition, several people not in the book say on camera that Monroe kept diaries with references to meetings with the Kennedy brothers, according to a staff member who has seen the report.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] "It set out to be a piece which would demonstrate that because of alleged relations between Robert Kennedy and John F.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Kennedy and Monroe, the presidency was compromised because organized crime was involved," he said.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] "Based on what has been uncovered so far, there was no evidence." Arledge's decision to kill the broadcast resulted in the subsequent decision of Geraldo Rivera to leave ABC entirely.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Rivera was a *20/20* correspondent but did not work on that story.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] He had been publicly critical of Arledge's decision.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Arledge, a champion and defender of Rivera, said he thought the story needed more work.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] The story probed purported affairs between actress Marilyn Monroe, President John F.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] On August 7, 2014, ABC announced that it would relaunch its radio network division, ABC Radio, on January 1, 2015.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] The change occurred following the announcement that Cumulus would replace its ABC News radio service with Westwood One News (via CNN).
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] On September 20, 2019, ABC Radio was renamed as ABC Audio as the network has evolved to offer a podcast portfolio and other forms of on-demand and linear content.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] In April 2018, it was announced that *FiveThirtyEight* would be transferred to ABC News from ESPN, Inc., majority owned by the Walt Disney Company.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] On September 10, 2018, ABC News launched a second attempt to extend its *Good Morning America* brand into the afternoon with *GMA3: What You Need to Know*.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] In May 2019, *ABC News Live*, a news focused streaming channel, was launched on Roku.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Following a reorganization of ABC's parent company, The Walt Disney Company which created the Walt Disney Direct-to-Consumer and International segment in March 2018, ABC News Digital and Live Streaming, including *ABC News Live* and *FiveThirtyEight*, were transferred to the new segment.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] In an October 2018 Simmons Research survey of 38 news organizations, ABC News was ranked the second most trusted news organization by Americans, behind *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] In December 2024, ABC's owner, the Walt Disney Company, settled a defamation lawsuit brought by Donald Trump against ABC News, by agreeing to donate $15 million to Trump's future presidential library foundation and paying $1 million in Trump's legal fees.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Disney also agreed to ABC and anchor George Stephanopoulos publishing a statement saying they regretted that Stephanopoulos, in an interview, had repeatedly said that Trump had been found liable for raping E.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] In November 2025, President Donald Trump became angry with an ABC News reporter for asking a question about the Jeffrey Epstein case and called for the revocation of the network's broadcasting license.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] The website initially had a dedicated staff of about 30.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] In addition to articles, it featured short video clips and audio from the start, delivered using RealAudio and RealVideo technology.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Some content was also available via America Online.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] In 2011, ABC News and Yahoo News announced a strategic partnership to share ABC's online reporting on Yahoo's website; the deal expanded in 2015 to include the Disney/ABC Television Group.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] In 2018, ABC News, and *Good Morning America* specifically, ended the hosting partnership with Yahoo, instead opting to continue separate web presences.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] The service is under the direction of Justin Dial, Vice President of Streaming Content, Seniboye Tienabeso, Executive Director of ABC News Live, Chandra Zeikel, Executive Producer and Eric Ortega, Executive Producer.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Satellite News Channel was a joint venture between ABC News and Group W that launched on June 21, 1982, as a satellite-delivered cable television network.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] SNC used footage from ABC News and seven Washington, D.C.–based crews and stories from other overseas networks to provide a rotating newscast every 20 minutes.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] However, this channel had difficulty getting clearance from cable systems, so ABC News and Group W decided to sell it to its competitor, CNN (a subsidiary of Time Warner's Turner Broadcasting System).
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] CNN ceased Satellite News Channel's operations on October 27, 1983.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] SNC was either replaced by CNN or CNN2 on most cable systems.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] ABC News Now was a 24-hour cable news network that launched on July 26, 2004, as a digital subchannel by ABC News, being the company's second attempt in the 24-hour cable news world after Satellite News Channel.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] It was offered via digital television, broadband and streaming video at ABCNews.com and on mobile phones.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] It delivered breaking news, headline news each half hour, and a wide range of entertainment and lifestyle programming.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] The channel was available in the United States and Europe.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Its Talk Back feature allowed viewers to voice their input by submitting videos and personal thoughts on controversial issues and current topics.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] It was shut down as a digital subchannel after its experimental phase ended with the Presidential inauguration in 2005.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] ABC News Now was replaced on cable providers with Fusion on October 28, 2013.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Fusion was a digital cable and satellite network owned and operated by Fusion Media Group, LLC, which was a joint venture between ABC News and Univision Communications.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] ABC and Univision formally announced their launch on May 2, 2012.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Launched on October 28, 2013, Fusion features a mix of traditional news and investigative programs along with satirical content aimed at English-speaking Hispanic and Latino American adults between the ages of 18 and 34.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] The network replaced ABC News Now, a mainly streaming service of ABC News content.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] In December 2015, it was reported that Disney was in talks to sell its stake in Fusion to Univision.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] The split was complete on April 21, 2016; Univision alone would continue to operate Fusion until December 31, 2021, when it shut down the network.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] In March 2024, Donald Trump filed a defamation lawsuit against ABC News and George Stephanopoulos for defamation, alleging that Stephanopoulos's statements during an interview of Trump on *This Week* were "false, intentional, malicious and designed to cause harm".
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Jean Carroll had sued Trump for rape and sexual assault; the jury in the case, *Carroll II*, had found him liable for sexual assault and awarded Carroll $5 million in damages.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] In July, ABC News moved to dismiss the case, citing Judge Kaplan's comments that Carroll's rape accusation was "substantially true"; the motion was rejected by the presiding judge.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] In December, after Trump had won the 2024 presidential election, ABC News settled the defamation lawsuit a day after a judge ruled that both Trump and Stephanopoulos were required to sit for depositions in the case.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Legal experts said that the settlement, which occurred prior to motions for summary judgments, was agreed to earlier than is typical in the pre-trial procedures of defamation cases.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] They said that it may have been linked to Trump's status as a president-elect or was negotiated to avoid turning over potentially damaging information in the discovery process.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] The *New York Times* reported that according to company insiders Disney leadership was concerned that a Trump-friendly jury in Florida might potentially award Trump a sum exceeding the settlement, to be followed by a risky appeals process.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] The terms of the settlement required ABC News to pay $15 million to Trump's presidential library and $1 million to cover Trump's legal fees, as well as issue a public apology expressing regret for Stephanopoulos's inaccurate claims against Trump.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] Coincidentally, that country's public broadcasting, the Australian Broadcasting Corporation, operates its unrelated news division that is also named ABC News.
[src:australian-kriol/abc-news-united-states] ABC News maintains a content-sharing agreement with the Nine Network, which also broadcasts *GMA* domestically in the early morning before its own breakfast program.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Humans first migrated to Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, and over time formed as many as 500 linguistic and territorial groups.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people once lived across large areas of the continental shelf that were later inundated by postglacial sea-level rise at the start of the Holocene inter-glacial period, reshaping coastal landscapes and separating Tasmania from the mainland.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people maintained extensive networks within the continent and certain groups maintained relationships with Torres Strait Islanders and the Makassar people of modern-day Indonesia.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Over the millennia, Aboriginal people developed complex trade networks, inter-cultural relationships, law and religions, which make up some of the oldest continuous cultures in the world.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] At the time of European colonisation of Australia, the Aboriginal people spoke more than 250 different languages, possessed varying degrees of technology, and lived in various types of settlements.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Languages (or dialects) and language-associated groups of people are connected with stretches of territory known as "Country", with which they have a profound spiritual connection.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Contemporary Aboriginal beliefs are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by later migrants, and contemporary issues.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Just over half hold secular or other spiritual beliefs or no religious affiliation; about 40% are Christian; and about 1% adhere to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared through dancing, stories, songlines, and art that collectively weave an ontology of modern daily life and ancient creation known as the Dreaming.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Studies of Aboriginal groups' genetic makeup are ongoing, but evidence suggests that they have genetic inheritance from ancient Asian peoples.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians and Papuans shared the same paleocontinent Sahul, although they became genetically distinct about 37,000 years ago.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians have a broadly shared, complex genetic history, but only in the last 200 years have they been defined by others as, and started to self-identify as, a single group.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal identity has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification, and community acceptance all of varying importance.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The 2021 census shows that there were 944,171 Aboriginal people, comprising 3.7% of Australia's population.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Over 80% of Aboriginal people today speak English at home, and about 77,000 speak an Indigenous language at home.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people, along with Torres Strait Islander people, suffer a number of severe health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Archeological evidence indicates that the ancestors of today's Aboriginal Australians first migrated to the continent 50,000 to 65,000 years ago.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] While there have been genomic studies placing arrival as late as 43,000 years ago, a 2025 study suggests that the peopling of Australia happened around 60,000 years ago, via two distinct routes.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Early human migration to Australia was achieved when it formed a part of the Sahul continent, connected to the island of New Guinea via a land bridge.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] This would have nevertheless required crossing the sea at the Wallace Line.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] It is also possible that people came by island-hopping via an island chain between Sulawesi and New Guinea, reaching North Western Australia via Timor.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] As sea levels rose, the people on the Australian mainland and nearby islands became increasingly isolated, some on Tasmania and some of the smaller offshore islands when the land was inundated at the start of the Holocene, the inter-glacial period that started about 11,700 years ago.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The modelling is based on data from archaeologists, anthropologists, ecologists, geneticists, climatologists, geomorphologists, and hydrologists.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The new models suggest that the first people may have landed in the Kimberley region in what is now Western Australia about 60,000 years ago, and had settled across the continent within 6,000 years.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians may have one of the oldest continuous cultures on earth.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] In Arnhem Land in the Northern Territory, oral histories comprising complex narratives have been passed down by Yolngu people through hundreds of generations.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The Aboriginal rock art, dated by modern techniques, shows that their culture has continued from ancient times.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Genetic studies have revealed that a population wave, termed East Eurasian Core, outgoing from the Iranian plateau during the Initial Upper Paleolithic period populated the Asia-Pacific region via a southern route dispersal.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] This wave is suggested to have expanded into the South and Southeast Asia region and subsequently diverged rapidly into the ancestors of Ancient Ancestral South Indians (AASI), Andamanese, East Asians, and Australasians, including Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians are genetically most closely related to other Oceanians, such as Papuans and Melanesians, who are collectively referred to as "Australasians," which can be described as "a deeply branching East Asian lineage".
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] This earlier group has been estimated to have possibly contributed around 2% ancestry to modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] 2017 found the bifurcation of Eastern Eurasians and Western Eurasians dates to at least 45,000 years ago, with indigenous Australians nested inside the Eastern Eurasian clade.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Genetic data on indigenous populations of Borneo and Malaysia showed them to be more closely related to other mainland Asian groups, than compared to the groups from Papua New Guinea and Australia.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] This indicates that populations in Australia were isolated for a long time from the rest of Southeast Asia.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] They remained untouched by migrations and population expansions into that area, which can be explained by the Wallace line.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The most common Y-chromosome haplogroups among Aboriginal Australians is C1b2, followed by haplogroups S and M; these latter haplogroups are also very frequent among Papuans.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] In a 2001 study, blood samples were collected from some Warlpiri people in the Northern Territory to study their genetic makeup (which is not representative of all Aboriginal peoples in Australia).
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The study concluded that the Warlpiri are descended from ancient Asians whose DNA is still somewhat present in Southeastern Asian groups, although greatly diminished.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The Warlpiri DNA lacks certain information found in modern Asian genomes, and carries information not found in other genomes.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] This reinforces the idea of ancient Aboriginal isolation.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Genetic data extracted in 2011 by Morten Rasmussen et al., who took a DNA sample from an early-20th-century lock of an Aboriginal person's hair, found that the Aboriginal ancestors probably migrated through South Asia and Maritime Southeast Asia, into Australia, where they stayed.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] As a result, outside of Africa, the Aboriginal peoples have continuously occupied the same territory longer than any other human populations.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] These findings suggest that modern Aboriginal Australians are the direct descendants of the eastern wave, who left Africa up to 75,000 years ago.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Examining DNA from a finger bone excavated in Siberia, researchers concluded that the Denisovans migrated from Siberia to tropical parts of Asia and that they interbred with modern humans in Southeast Asia 44,000 years BP, before Australia separated from New Guinea approximately 11,700 years BP.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] They contributed DNA to Aboriginal Australians and to present-day New Guineans and an indigenous tribe in the Philippines known as Mamanwa.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] This study confirms Aboriginal Australians as one of the oldest living populations in the world.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] They are possibly the oldest outside Africa, and they may have the oldest continuous culture on the planet.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] A 2016 study at the University of Cambridge suggests that it was about 50,000 years ago that these peoples reached Sahul (the supercontinent consisting of present-day Australia and its islands and New Guinea).
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The sea levels rose and isolated Australia about 10,000 years ago, but Aboriginal Australians and Papuans diverged from each other earlier, genetically, about 37,000 years BP, possibly because the remaining land bridge was impassable.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] This isolation makes the Aboriginal people the world's oldest culture.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The study also found evidence of an unknown hominin group, distantly related to Denisovans, with whom the Aboriginal and Papuan ancestors must have interbred, leaving a trace of about 4% in most Aboriginal Australians' genome.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] There is, however, increased genetic diversity among Aboriginal Australians based on geographical distribution.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] 2021 analysed a Holocene hunter-gatherer sample ("Leang Panninge") from South Sulawesi, which shares high amounts of genetic drift with Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] This suggests that a population split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The sample also shows genetic affinity with East Asians and the Andamanese people of South Asia.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The authors note that this hunter-gatherer sample can be modelled with ~50% Australian/Papuan-related ancestry and either with ~50% East Asian or Andamanese Onge ancestry, highlighting the deep split between Leang Panninge and Aboriginal/Papuans.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] 2021 found that Philippines Negrito people split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans before the latter two diverged from each other, but after their common ancestor diverged from the ancestor of East Asian peoples.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Like Papuans, it's believed that Aboriginal Australians underwent a secondary admixture event with Altai-related Denisovan populations after they diverged from the ancestors of East Asians, who already mixed with Denisovans.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] This event was also separate from the admixture event experienced by Filipino Negritos, explaining why Aboriginal Australians and Papuans have relatively lower Denisovan ancestry.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Based on a reevaluation of mitogenomes, Gandini et al.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] 2025 proposed a "long chronology", which suggested an earlier settlement of Sahul by two migration routes about ~60 ka.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] One route came from northern Sunda via the Philippine archipelago whilst the other came from southern Sunda via Mainland Southeast Asia, with both routes ultimately tracing back to South Asia.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The settlers that undertook these routes were ancestral to populations indigenous to Australia, New Guinea and Oceania, and were also related to other East Eurasians instead of belonging to a separate wave.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The dingo reached Australia about 4,000 years ago.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Near that time, there were changes in language (with the Pama-Nyungan language family spreading over most of the mainland), and in stone tool technology.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The first type of evidence comes from a 2013 study by the Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology using large-scale genotyping data from a pool of Aboriginal Australians, New Guineans, island Southeast Asians, and Indians.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] It found that the New Guinea and Mamanwa (Philippines area) groups diverged from the Aboriginal about 36,000 years ago (there is supporting evidence that these populations are descended from migrants taking an early "southern route" out of Africa, before other groups in the area).
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Also the Indian and Australian populations mixed long before European contact, with this gene flow occurring during the Holocene (c.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The researchers had two theories for this: either some Indians had contact with people in Indonesia who eventually transferred those Indian genes to Aboriginal Australians, or a group of Indians migrated from India to Australia and intermingled with the locals directly.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] However, a 2016 study in *Current Biology* by Anders Bergström et al. excluded the Y chromosome as providing evidence for recent gene flow from India into Australia.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The study authors sequenced 13 Aboriginal Australian Y chromosomes using recent advances in gene sequencing technology.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] They investigated their divergence times from Y chromosomes in other continents, including comparing the haplogroup C chromosomes.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] They found a divergence time of about 54,100 years between the Sahul C chromosome and its closest relative C5, as well as about 54,300 years between haplogroups K*/M and their closest haplogroups R and Q.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The deep divergence time of 50,000-plus years with the South Asian chromosome and "the fact that the Aboriginal Australian Cs share a more recent common ancestor with Papuan Cs" excludes any recent genetic contact.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] They attributed the disparity between their results and previous findings to improvements in technology; none of the other studies had utilised complete Y chromosome sequencing, which has the highest precision.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] For example, use of a ten Y STRs method has been shown to massively underestimate divergence times.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Bergström's 2018 doctoral thesis looking at the population of Sahul suggests that other than relatively recent admixture, the populations of the region appear to have been genetically independent from the rest of the world since their divergence about 50,000 years ago.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] He writes "There is no evidence for South Asian gene flow to Australia ....
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians possess inherited abilities to adapt to a wide range of environmental temperatures in various ways.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] A study in 1958 comparing cold adaptation in the desert-dwelling Pitjantjatjara people compared with a group of European people showed that the cooling adaptation of the Aboriginal group differed from that of the Europeans, and that they were able to sleep more soundly through a cold desert night.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] A 2014 Cambridge University study found that a beneficial mutation in two genes that regulate thyroxine, a hormone involved in regulating body metabolism, helps to regulate body temperature in response to fever.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The effect of this is that the desert people are able to have a higher body temperature without accelerating the activity of the whole of the body, which can be especially detrimental in childhood diseases.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] This helps protect people to survive the side-effects of infection.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] It is estimated that the Indigenous Australian population at the time of first European settlement numbered at least 314,500 people.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Based on the 2021 census, the Australian Bureau of Statistics estimates there were 901,655 Aboriginal Australians, and 42,516 who identified as both Aboriginal Australian and Torres Strait Islander.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] These groups comprise 3.7% of the total Australian population.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] 39,538 people identified as Torres Strait Islander, which is a different ethnic group from Aboriginal Australian.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Based on initial 2021 census counts, the Aboriginal and Torres Strait islander population grew 25.2%, since the previous census in 2016.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Demographic factors – births, deaths and migration – accounted for 43.5% of the increase (71,086 people).
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] In turn, 76.2% of that increase was attributed to people aged 0–19 years in 2021, broken down as 52.5% for 0–4 year olds (births since 2016) and 23.7% for 5–19 year olds.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Reasons for the increase in Aboriginal population also include non-demographic factors.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] These include changes in individuals' identification as Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander in different censuses, and individuals completing a census form in 2021 but not in 2016.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] These factors accounted for 56.5% of the increase in the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander population.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Indigenous Australians (including Torres Strait Islanders) are less likely to live in the major Australian cities than are non-Indigenous Australians (41% compared with 73%).
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Although humans arrived in Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, it is possible that the ancestor language of existing Aboriginal languages is as recent as 12,000 years old.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Over 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] As of 2021, 84% of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders spoke only English at home.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018-19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use are endangered.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] According to the 2021 census, the classifiable Aboriginal languages with the most speakers are Kriol (7,403), Djambarrpuyngu (3,839), Pitjantjatjara (3,399), Warlpiri (2,592), Murrinh Patha (2,063) and Tiwi (2,053).
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] There were also over 10,000 people who spoke an Indigenous language that could not be further defined or classified.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] A number of English-based creoles have arisen in Australia after European contact, of which Kriol is among the strongest and fastest-growing Aboriginal languages.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Kriol is spoken in the Northern Territory and Western Australia.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] It is estimated that there are 20,000 to 30,000 speakers of Indigenous creole languages.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Before British colonisation, there were perhaps five to sixteen languages on Tasmania, possibly related to one another in four language families.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The last speaker of a traditional Tasmanian language, Fanny Cochrane Smith, died in 1905.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Palawa kani is an in-progress constructed language, built from a composite of surviving words from various Tasmanian Aboriginal languages.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Traditional Indigenous languages often incorporated sign systems to aid communication with the hearing impaired, to complement verbal communication, and to replace verbal communication when the spoken language was forbidden for cultural reasons.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Many of these sign systems are still in use.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Dispersing across the Australian continent over time, the ancient people expanded and differentiated into distinct groups, each with its own language and culture.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] More than 400 distinct Australian Aboriginal peoples have been identified, distinguished by names designating their ancestral languages, dialects, or distinctive speech patterns.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] According to noted anthropologist, archaeologist and sociologist Harry Lourandos, historically, these groups lived in three main cultural areas, the Northern, Southern and Central cultural areas.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The Northern and Southern areas, having richer natural marine and woodland resources, were more densely populated than the Central area.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Other group names are based on the language group or specific dialect spoken.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] These also coincide with geographical regions of varying sizes.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] However, these lists are neither exhaustive nor definitive, and there are overlaps.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Different approaches have been taken by non-Aboriginal scholars in trying to understand and define Aboriginal culture and societies, some focusing on the micro-level (tribe, clan, etc.), and others on shared languages and cultural practices spread over large regions defined by ecological factors.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Anthropologists have encountered many difficulties in trying to define what constitutes an Aboriginal people/community/group/tribe, let alone naming them.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Knowledge of pre-colonial Aboriginal cultures and societal groupings is still largely dependent on the observers' interpretations, which were filtered through colonial ways of viewing societies.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Some Aboriginal peoples identify as one of several saltwater, freshwater, rainforest or desert peoples.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The term *Aboriginal Australians* includes many distinct peoples who have developed across Australia for over 50,000 years.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] These peoples have a broadly shared, complex, genetic history, but it is only in the last two hundred years that they have been defined and have started to self-identify as a single group socio-politically.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] While some preferred the term *Aborigine* to *Aboriginal* in the past, as the latter was seen to have more directly discriminatory legal origins, use of the term *Aborigine* has declined in recent decades, as many consider the term an offensive and racist hangover from Australia's colonial era.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The definition of the term *Aboriginal* has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification and community acceptance all being of varying importance.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The term *Indigenous Australians* refers to Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islander peoples, and the term is conventionally only used when both groups are included in the topic being addressed, or by self-identification by a person as Indigenous.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] As of 2021, 51% of Indigenous people stated that they held a secular or other spiritual belief or no religious affiliation; 41% were affiliated to Christianity; and 1% were affiliated to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Australian Indigenous people have beliefs unique to each mob (tribe) and have a strong connection to the land.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Contemporary Indigenous Australian beliefs are a complex mixture, varying by region and individual across the continent.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] They are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by Europeans, and contemporary issues.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared by dancing, stories, songlines and art—especially Papunya Tula (dot painting)—collectively telling the story of creation known as The Dreamtime.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Additionally, traditional healers were also custodians of important Dreaming stories as well as their medical roles (for example the Ngangkari in the Western desert).
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Some core structures and themes are shared across the continent with details and additional elements varying between language and cultural groups.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] For example, in The Dreamtime of most regions, a spirit creates the earth then tells the humans to treat the animals and the earth in a way that is respectful to land.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] In Northern Territory this spirit is commonly said to be a huge snake or snakes that weaved its way through the earth and sky making the mountains and oceans.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] But in other places the spirits who created the world are known as wandjina rain and water spirits.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Major ancestral spirits include the Rainbow Serpent, Baiame, Dirawong and Bunjil.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Similarly, the Arrernte people of central Australia believed that humanity originated from great superhuman ancestors who brought the sun, wind and rain as a result of breaking through the surface of the Earth when waking from their slumber.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Many Dreamtime stories are still believed by many Indigenous Australians to this day.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Taken as a whole, Aboriginal Australians, along with Torres Strait Islander people, have a number of health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Due to the aforementioned disadvantage, Aboriginal Australian communities experience a higher rate of suicide, as compared to non-indigenous communities.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] These issues stem from a variety of different causes unique to indigenous communities, such as historical trauma, socioeconomic disadvantage, and decreased access to education and health care.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Also, this problem largely affects indigenous youth, as many indigenous youth may feel disconnected from their culture.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] To combat the increased suicide rate, many researchers have suggested that the inclusion of more cultural aspects into suicide prevention programs would help to combat mental health issues within the community.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Past studies have found that many indigenous leaders and community members, do in fact, want more culturally-aware health care programs.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Similarly, culturally-relative programs targeting indigenous youth have actively challenged suicide ideation among younger indigenous populations, with many social and emotional wellbeing programs using cultural information to provide coping mechanisms and improving mental health.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] Indigenous communities in remote Australia are often small, isolated towns with basic facilities, on traditionally owned land.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] These communities have between 20 and 300 inhabitants and are often closed to outsiders for cultural reasons.
[src:australian-kriol/aboriginal-australians] The long-term viability and resilience of Aboriginal communities in desert areas has been discussed by scholars and policy-makers.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] An **adjective** (abbreviated **ADJ**) is a word that describes or defines a noun or noun phrase.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Its semantic role is to change information given by the noun.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] The adjective is considered one of the main parts of speech of the English language, although historically they were classed together with nouns.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Nowadays, certain words that usually had been classified as adjectives, including *the*, *this*, *my*, etc., typically are classed separately, as determiners.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Depending on the language, an adjective can precede a corresponding noun on a prepositive basis or it can follow a corresponding noun on a postpositive basis.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Structural, contextual, and style considerations can impinge on the pre-or post-position of an adjective in a given instance of its occurrence.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Adjectives feature as a part of speech (word class) in most languages.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] In some languages, the words that serve the semantic function of adjectives are categorized together with some other class, such as nouns or verbs.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] In the phrase *a Ford car*, *Ford* is unquestionably a noun but its function is adjectival (noun adjunct, see below): to modify *car*.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] In some languages adjectives can function as nouns: for example, the Spanish phrase *un rojo* means 'a red [one]'.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] This is also possible in English, see above.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] As for "confusion" with verbs, rather than an adjective meaning "big", a language might have a verb that means "to be big" and could then use an attributive verb construction analogous to "big-being house" to express what in English is called a "big house".
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Such an analysis is possible for the grammar of Standard Chinese and Korean, for example.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Different languages do not use adjectives in exactly the same situations.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] For example, where English uses *"*to be *hungry*" (*hungry* being an adjective), Dutch, French, and Spanish use "*honger hebben*", "*avoir faim*", and "*tener hambre*" respectively (literally "to have hunger", the words for "hunger" being nouns).
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Similarly, where Hebrew uses the adjective זקוק‎ (*zaqūq*, roughly "in need of" or "needing"), English uses the verb "to need".
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] In languages that have adjectives as a word class, it is usually an open class; that is, it is relatively common for new adjectives to be formed via such processes as derivation.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] However, Bantu languages are well known for having only a small closed class of adjectives, and new adjectives are not easily derived.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Similarly, native Japanese adjectives (*i*-adjectives) are considered a closed class (as are native verbs), although nouns (an open class) may be used in the genitive to convey some adjectival meanings, and there is also the separate open class of adjectival nouns (*na*-adjectives).
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Many languages (including English) distinguish between adjectives, which qualify nouns and pronouns, and adverbs, which mainly modify verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Not all languages make this exact distinction; many (including English) have words that can function as either.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] For example, in English, *fast* is an adjective in "a *fast* car" (where it qualifies the noun *car*) but an adverb in "he drove *fast*" (where it modifies the verb *drove*).
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] A German word like *klug* ("clever(ly)") takes endings when used as an attributive adjective but not when used adverbially.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Whether these are distinct parts of speech or distinct usages of the same part of speech is a question of analysis.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] While German linguistic terminology distinguishes *adverbiale* from *adjektivische Formen*, German refers to both as *Eigenschaftswörter* ("property words").
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Linguists today distinguish determiners from adjectives, considering them to be two separate parts of speech (or *lexical categories*).
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Determiners formerly were considered to be adjectives in some of their uses.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Determiners function neither as nouns nor pronouns but instead characterize a nominal element within a particular context.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] They generally do this by indicating definiteness (*a* vs.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] An adjective acts as the head of an *adjective phrase* or *adjectival phrase* (AP).
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] In the simplest case, an adjective phrase consists solely of the adjective; more complex adjective phrases may contain one or more adverbs modifying the adjective ("*very* strong"), or one or more complements (such as "worth *several dollars*", "full *of toys*", or "eager *to please*").
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] In English, attributive adjective phrases that include complements typically follow the noun that they qualify ("an evildoer *devoid of redeeming qualities*").
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] In many languages (including English) it is possible for nouns to modify other nouns.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Unlike adjectives, nouns acting as modifiers (called *attributive nouns* or *noun adjuncts*) usually are not predicative; a beautiful park is beautiful, but a car park is not "car".
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] The modifier often indicates origin ("*Virginia* reel"), purpose ("*work* clothes"), semantic patient ("*man* eater") or semantic subject ("*child* actor"); however, it may generally indicate almost any semantic relationship.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] It is also common for adjectives to be derived from nouns, as in *boyish*, *birdlike*, *behavioral (behavioural)*, *famous*, *manly*, *angelic*, and so on.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Many languages have participle forms that can act as noun modifiers either alone or as the head of a phrase.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Sometimes participles develop into functional usage as adjectives.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Examples in English include *relieved* (the past participle of *relieve*), used as an adjective in passive voice constructs such as "I am so *relieved* to see you".
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Other examples include *spoken* (the past participle of *speak*) and *going* (the present participle of *go*), which function as attribute adjectives in such phrases as "the *spoken* word" and "the *going* rate".
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Other constructs that often modify nouns include prepositional phrases (as in "a rebel *without a cause*"), relative clauses (as in "the man *who wasn't there*"), and infinitive phrases (as in "a cake *to die for*").
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Some nouns can also take complements such as content clauses (as in "the idea *that I would do that*"), but these are not commonly considered modifiers.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] For more information about possible modifiers and dependents of nouns, see Components of noun phrases.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] In Australian Aboriginal languages, the distinction between adjectives and nouns is typically thought weak, and many of the languages only use nouns, or nouns with a limited set of adjective-deriving affixes, to modify other nouns.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] In languages that have a subtle adjective-noun distinction, one way to tell them apart is that a modifying adjective can come to stand in for an entire elided noun phrase, while a modifying noun cannot.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] For example, in Bardi, the adjective *moorrooloo* 'little' in the phrase *moorrooloo* *baawa* 'little child' can stand on its own to mean 'the little one', while the attributive noun *aamba* 'man' in the phrase *aamba baawa* 'male child' cannot stand for the whole phrase to mean 'the male one'.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] In other languages, like Warlpiri, nouns and adjectives are lumped together beneath the nominal umbrella because of their shared syntactic distribution as arguments of predicates.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] The only thing distinguishing them is that some nominals seem to semantically denote entities (typically nouns in English) and some nominals seem to denote attributes (typically adjectives in English).
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] In many languages, attributive adjectives usually occur in a specific order.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] In general, the adjective order in English can be summarised as: opinion, size, age or shape, colour, origin, material, purpose.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Other language authorities, like the *Cambridge Dictionary*, state that shape precedes rather than follows age.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Determiners and postdeterminers—articles, numerals, and other limiters (e.g.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] *three* blind mice)—come before attributive adjectives in English.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Although certain combinations of determiners can appear before a noun, they are far more circumscribed than adjectives in their use—typically, only a single determiner would appear before a noun or noun phrase (including any attributive adjectives).
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Size – adjectives denoting physical size (e.g.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Shape or physical quality – adjectives describing more detailed physical attributes than overall size (e.g.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Colour – adjectives denoting colour or pattern (e.g.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Origin – denominal adjectives denoting source (e.g.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] This means that, in English, adjectives pertaining to size precede adjectives pertaining to age ("little old", not "old little"), which in turn generally precede adjectives pertaining to colour ("old white", not "white old").
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] This order may be more rigid in some languages than others; in some, like Spanish, it may only be a default (*unmarked*) word order, with other orders being permissible.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Other languages, such as Tagalog, follow their adjectival orders as rigidly as English.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] The normal adjectival order of English may be overridden in certain circumstances, especially when one adjective is being fronted or with ablaut reduplication.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] For example, the usual order of adjectives in English would result in the phrase "the bad big wolf" (opinion before size), but instead, the usual phrase is "the big bad wolf".
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Owing partially to borrowings from French, English has some adjectives that follow the noun as postmodifiers, called postpositive adjectives, as in *time immemorial* and *attorney general*.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Adjectives may even change meaning depending on whether they precede or follow, as in *proper*: "They live in a *proper town*" (a real town, not a village) vs.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] "They live in the *town proper* (in the town itself, not in the suburbs).
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] In many languages, some adjectives are *comparable* and the measure of comparison is called *degree*.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] For example, a person may be "polite", but another person may be "*more* polite", and a third person may be the "*most* polite" of the three.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] The word "more" here modifies the adjective "polite" to indicate a comparison is being made, and "most" modifies the adjective to indicate an absolute comparison (a *superlative*).
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Among languages that allow adjectives to be compared, different means are used to indicate comparison.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Some languages do not distinguish between comparative and superlative forms.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Other languages allow adjectives to be compared but do not have a special comparative form of the adjective.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] In such cases, as in some Australian Aboriginal languages, case-marking, such as the ablative case, may be used to indicate one entity has more of an adjectival quality than (i.e.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Another way to convey comparison is by incorporating the words "more" and "most".
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] There is no simple rule to decide which means is correct for any given adjective, however.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] The general tendency is for simpler adjectives and those from Anglo-Saxon to take the suffixes, while longer adjectives and those from French, Latin, or Greek do not—but sometimes the *sound* of the word is the deciding factor.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Many adjectives do not naturally lend themselves to comparison.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] For example, some English speakers would argue that it does not make sense to say that one thing is "more ultimate" than another, or that something is "most ultimate", since the word "ultimate" is already absolute in its semantics.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Such adjectives are called *non-comparable* or *absolute*.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Nevertheless, native speakers will frequently play with the raised forms of adjectives of this sort.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Although "pregnant" is logically non-comparable (either one is pregnant or not), one may hear a sentence like "She looks more and more pregnant each day".
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Comparative and superlative forms are also occasionally used for other purposes than comparison.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] In Italian, superlatives are frequently used to put strong emphasis on an adjective: *bellissimo* means "most beautiful", but is in fact more commonly heard in the sense "extremely beautiful".
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Attributive adjectives and other noun modifiers may be used either *restrictively* (helping to identify the noun's referent, hence "restricting" its reference) or *non-restrictively* (helping to describe a noun).
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Here "difficult" is restrictive – it tells which tasks he avoids, distinguishing these from the easy ones: "Only those tasks that are difficult".
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] In English, restrictiveness is not marked on adjectives but is marked on relative clauses (the difference between "the man *who recognized me* was there" and "the man, *who recognized me*, was there" being one of restrictiveness).
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] In some languages, adjectives alter their form to reflect the gender, case and number of the noun that they describe.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Here, a distinction may be made between attributive and predicative usage.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] In English, adjectives never agree, whereas in French, they always agree.
[src:australian-kriol/adjective] Semanticist Barbara Partee classifies adjectives semantically as intersective, subsective, or nonsubsective, with nonsubsective adjectives being plain nonsubsective or privative.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In linguistics, **adpositions** are a class of words used to express spatial or temporal relations (*in*, *under*, *towards*, *behind*, *ago*, etc.) or mark various semantic roles (*of*, *for*).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] The most common adpositions are **prepositions** (which precede their complement) and **postpositions** (which follow their complement).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] An adposition typically combines with a noun phrase, this being called its complement, or sometimes object.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Some languages that use a different word order have postpositions instead (like Turkic languages) or have both types (like Finnish).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] The phrase formed by an adposition together with its complement is called an adpositional phrase (or prepositional phrase, postpositional phrase, etc.).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Such a phrase can function as a grammatical modifier or complement in a wide range of types of phrases.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] A less common type of adposition is the **circumposition**, which consists of two parts that appear on each side of the complement.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Other terms sometimes used for particular types of adposition include ***ambiposition***, ***inposition*** and ***interposition***.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Some linguists use the word *preposition* in place of *adposition* regardless of the applicable word order.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] The word *preposition* comes from Latin: *prae-* prefix (pre- prefix) ("before") and Latin: *ponere* ("to put").
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] This refers to the situation in Latin and Greek (and in English), where such words are placed before their complement (except sometimes in Ancient Greek), and are hence "pre-positioned".
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In some languages, including Sindhi, Hindustani, Turkish, Hungarian, Korean, and Japanese, the same kinds of words typically come after their complement.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] To indicate this, they are called *postpositions* (using the prefix *post-*, from Latin *post* meaning "behind, after").
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] There are also some cases where the function is performed by two parts coming before and after the complement; this is called a *circumposition* (from Latin *circum-* prefix "around").
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In some languages, for example Finnish, some adpositions can be used as both prepositions and postpositions.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Prepositions, postpositions and circumpositions are collectively known as *adpositions* (using the Latin prefix *ad-*, meaning "to").
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] However, some linguists prefer to use the well-known and longer-established term *preposition* in place of *adposition*, irrespective of position relative to the complement.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] An adposition typically combines with exactly one complement, most often a noun phrase (or, in a different analysis, a determiner phrase).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In English, this is generally a noun (or something functioning as a noun, e.g., a gerund), together with its specifier and modifiers such as articles, adjectives, etc.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] The complement is sometimes called the *object* of the adposition.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] The resulting phrase, formed by the adposition together with its complement, is called an adpositional phrase or prepositional phrase (PP) (or for specificity, a postpositional or circumpositional phrase).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] An adposition establishes a grammatical relationship that links its complement to another word or phrase in the context.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] It also generally establishes a semantic relationship, which may be spatial (*in*, *on*, *under*, ...), temporal (*after*, *during*, ...), or of some other type (*of*, *for*, *via*, ...).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] The World Atlas of Language Structures treats a word as an adposition if it takes a noun phrase as a complement and indicates the grammatical or semantic relationship of that phrase to the verb in the containing clause.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Some examples of the use of English prepositions are given below.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In each case, the prepositional phrase appears in *italics*, the preposition within it appears in ***bold***, and the preposition's complement is underlined.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] As demonstrated in some of the examples, more than one prepositional phrase may act as an adjunct to the same word.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In the last of these examples the complement has the form of an adverb, which has been nominalised to serve as a noun phrase; see Different forms of complement, below.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] An adposition may determine the grammatical case of its complement.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In English, the complements of prepositions take the objective case where available (*from him*, not **from he*).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Some languages have cases that are used exclusively after prepositions (prepositional case), or special forms of pronouns for use after prepositions (prepositional pronoun).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] The functions of adpositions overlap with those of case markings (for example, the meaning of the English preposition *of* is expressed in many languages by a genitive case ending), but adpositions are classed as syntactic elements, while case markings are morphological.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Adpositions themselves are usually non-inflecting ("invariant"): they do not have paradigms of the form (such as tense, case, gender, etc.) the same way that verbs, adjectives, and nouns can.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] There are exceptions, though, such as prepositions that have fused with a pronominal object to form inflected prepositions.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] As noted above, adpositions are referred to by various terms, depending on their position relative to the complement.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] While the term *preposition* sometimes denotes any adposition, its stricter meaning refers only to one that precedes its complement.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In certain grammatical constructions, the complement of a preposition may be absent or may be moved from its position directly following the preposition.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] This may be referred to as preposition stranding (see also below), as in "Whom did you go **with**?" and "There's only one thing worse than being talked **about**." There are also some (mainly colloquial) expressions in which a preposition's complement may be omitted, such as "I'm going to the park.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] A *postposition* follows its complement to form a postpositional phrase.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] An adposition like the above, which can be either a preposition or a postposition, can be called an **ambiposition**.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] However, *ambiposition* may also be used to refer to a circumposition (see below), or to a word that appears to function as a preposition and postposition simultaneously, as in the Vedic Sanskrit construction (noun-1) *ā* (noun-2), meaning "from (noun-1) to (noun-2)".
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Whether a language has primarily prepositions or postpositions is seen as an aspect of its typological classification, and tends to correlate with other properties related to head directionality.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Since an adposition is regarded as the head of its phrase, prepositional phrases are head-initial (or right-branching), while postpositional phrases are head-final (or left-branching).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] There is a tendency for languages that feature postpositions also to have other head-final features, such as verbs that follow their objects; and for languages that feature prepositions to have other head-initial features, such as verbs that precede their objects.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] This is only a tendency, however; an example of a language that behaves differently is Latin, which employs mostly prepositions, even though it typically places verbs after their objects.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] A *circumposition* consists of two or more parts, positioned on both sides of the complement.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Circumpositions are very common in Pashto and Kurdish.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Most such phrases, however, can be analyzed as having a different hierarchical structure (such as a prepositional phrase modifying a following adverb).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] The Chinese example could be analyzed as a prepositional phrase headed by *cóng* ("from"), taking the locative noun phrase *bīngxīang lǐ* ("refrigerator inside") as its complement.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] An **inposition** is a rare type of adposition that appears between parts of a complex complement.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] For example, in the native Californian Timbisha language, the phrase "from a mean cold" can be translated using the word order "cold from mean"—the inposition follows the noun but precedes any following modifiers that form part of the same noun phrase.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] The Latin word *cum* is also commonly used as an inposition, as in the phrase *summa cum laude*, meaning "with highest praise", lit.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] The term **interposition** has been used for adpositions in structures such as *word **for** word*, French *coup **sur** coup* ("one after another, repeatedly"), and Russian друг **с** другом ("one with the other").
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] This is not a case of an adposition appearing inside its complement, as the two nouns do not form a single phrase (there is no phrase **word word*, for example); such uses have more of a coordinating character.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Preposition stranding is a syntactic construct in which a preposition occurs somewhere other than immediately before its complement.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] For example, in the English sentence "What did you sit on?" the preposition *on* has *what* as its complement, but *what* is moved to the start of the sentence, because it is an interrogative word.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] This sentence is much more common and natural than the equivalent sentence without stranding: "On what did you sit?" Preposition stranding is commonly found in English, as well as North Germanic languages such as Swedish.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Preposition stranding is also found in some Niger–Congo languages such as Vata and Gbadi, and in some North American varieties of French.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Some prescriptive English grammars teach that prepositions cannot end a sentence, although there is no rule prohibiting that use.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Similar rules arose during the rise of classicism, when they were applied to English in imitation of classical languages such as Latin.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Otto Jespersen, in his *Essentials of English Grammar* (first published 1933), commented on this definition-derived rule: "...nor need a preposition (Latin: *praepositio*) stand before the word it governs (go the fools *among* (Sh[akespeare]); What are you laughing *at*?).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Simple adpositions consist of a single word (*on*, *in*, *for*, *towards*, etc.).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Complex adpositions consist of a group of words that act as one unit.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Examples of complex prepositions in English include *in spite of*, *with respect to*, *except for*, *by dint of*, and *next to*.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] The distinction between simple and complex adpositions is not clear-cut.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Many complex adpositions are derived from simple forms (e.g., *with + in* → *within*, *by + side* → *beside*) through grammaticalisation.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] This change takes time, and during the transitional stages, the adposition acts in some ways like a single word, and in other ways like a multi-word unit.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] The distinction between complex adpositions and free combinations of words is not a black-and-white issue: complex adpositions (in English, "prepositional idioms") can be more fossilized or less fossilized.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In English, this applies to a number of structures of the form "preposition + (article) + noun + preposition", such as *in front of*, *for the sake of*.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Marginal prepositions are prepositions that have affinities with other word classes, most notably participles.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Marginal prepositions behave like prepositions but derive from other parts of speech.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Some marginal prepositions in English include *barring*, *concerning*, *considering*, *excluding*, *failing*, *following*, *including*, *notwithstanding*, *regarding*, and *respecting*.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In descriptions of some languages, prepositions are divided into **proper** (or *essential*) and **improper** (or *accidental*).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] A preposition is called improper if it is some other part of speech being used in the same way as a preposition.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Examples of simple and complex prepositions that have been so classified include *prima di* ("before") and *davanti (a)* ("in front of") in Italian, and *ergo* ("on account of") and *causa* ("for the sake of") in Latin.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In reference to Ancient Greek, however, an improper preposition is one that cannot also serve as a prefix to a verb.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] As noted above, adpositions typically have noun phrases as complements.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] The word *to* when it precedes the infinitive in English is not a preposition, but rather is a grammatical particle outside of any main word class.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In other cases, the complement may have the form of an adjective or adjective phrase, or an adverbial.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] This may be regarded as a complement representing a different syntactic category, or simply as an atypical form of noun phrase (see nominalization).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In the last example, the complement of the preposition *from* is in fact another prepositional phrase.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] The resulting sequence of two prepositions (*from under*) may be regarded as a complex preposition; in some languages, such a sequence may be represented by a single word, as Russian из-под *iz-pod* ("from under").
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] It is more commonly assumed, however, that *Sammy* and the following predicate forms a *small clause*, which then becomes the single complement of the preposition.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Adpositions can be used to express a wide range of semantic relations between their complement and the rest of the context.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] The relations expressed may be spatial (denoting location or direction), temporal (denoting position in time), or relations expressing comparison, content, agent, instrument, means, manner, cause, purpose, reference, etc.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Most common adpositions are highly polysemous (they have various different meanings).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In many cases, a primary, spatial meaning becomes extended to non-spatial uses by metaphorical or other processes.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Because of the variety of meanings, a single adposition often has many possible equivalents in another language, depending on the exact context.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] This can cause difficulties in foreign language learning.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Usage can also vary between dialects of the same language (for example, American English has *on the weekend*, whereas British English uses *at the weekend*).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In some contexts (as in the case of some phrasal verbs) the choice of adposition may be determined by another element in the construction or be fixed by the construction as a whole.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Here the adposition may have little independent semantic content of its own, and there may be no clear reason why the particular adposition is used rather than another.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Spatial meanings of adpositions may be either *directional* or *static*.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] A directional meaning usually involves motion in a particular direction ("Kay went **to** the store"), the direction in which something leads or points ("A path **into** the woods"), or the extent of something ("The fog stretched **from** London **to** Paris").
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] A static meaning indicates only a location ("**at** the store", "**behind** the chair", "**on** the moon").
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Some prepositions can have both uses: "he sat **in** the water" (static); "he jumped in the water" (probably directional).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In English and many other languages, prepositional phrases with static meaning are commonly used as predicative expressions after a copula ("Bob is at the store"); this may happen with some directional prepositions as well ("Bob is from Australia"), but this is less common.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Directional prepositional phrases combine mostly with verbs that indicate movement ("Jay is going into her bedroom", but not *"Jay is lying down into her bedroom").
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Directional meanings can be further divided into *telic* and *atelic*.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Telic prepositional phrases imply movement all the way to the endpoint ("she ran to the fence"), while atelic ones do not ("she ran towards the fence").
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Static meanings can be divided into *projective* and *non-projective*, where projective meanings are those whose understanding requires knowledge of the perspective or point of view.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] For example, the meaning of "behind the rock" is likely to depend on the position of the speaker (projective), whereas the meaning of "on the desk" is not (non-projective).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Sometimes the interpretation is ambiguous, as in "behind the house," which may mean either at the natural back of the house or on the opposite side of the house from the speaker.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Some languages feature inflected adpositions—adpositions (usually prepositions) marked for grammatical person and/or grammatical number to give meanings such as "on me," "from you," etc.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In the Indo-European languages this phenomenon is mostly confined to the Celtic languages like Welsh and Irish.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Polish also allows some degree of combining prepositions with pronouns in the third person.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] The majority of Welsh prepositions can be inflected.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] This is achieved by having a preposition such as *o* ('of/from') + a linking element; in the case of *o* this is *-hon-* + the assimilated pronoun element, resulting in *ohon-* being the preposition's "stem" form.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] It is common in speech for the pronoun to be present after the preposition, but it can be omitted.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Unless used with a pronoun the form is always *o* and not the "stem", e.g.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] The following table gives the inflected forms of the preposition *o* ('of/from').
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] The optional pronouns that follow the inflected forms are given in parentheses.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Inflected prepositions are found in Semitic languages, including Hebrew, Arabic, Assyrian Neo-Aramaic and Amharic.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] For example, the Arabic preposition على (/ʕalaː) 'on' inflects as علَيَّ (/ʕalajːa/) 'on me', علَيْكَ (/ʕalajka/) 'on you (M.SG)', علَيْهِ (/ʕalajhi/) 'on him', etc.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Some Iranic languages, including Persian, have developed inflected prepositions.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] For example, Persian *az u* 'from him/her' becomes *azaš*; *bā šomā* 'with you PL' becomes *bāhātun*.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In Iberian Romance languages such as Spanish and Portuguese, the preposition *con* or *com* 'with' has special forms incorporating certain pronouns (depending on the language).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] For example, in Spanish and Asturian *conmigo* means 'with me'.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Historically, this developed from the Latin use of *cum* 'with' after a pronoun, as in *mecum* 'with me'.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Bororo, an indigenous language of Brazil, uses postpositions in all contexts: *tori ji* 'about the mountains'.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] When these modify a pronoun rather than a full noun, the phrase contracts into an inflected postposition (and therefore looks like a pronominal prefix, rather than a suffix as in the examples above: *bagai* 'for', *i-wagai* 'for me').
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] There are often similarities in form between adpositions and adverbs.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Some adverbs are derived from the fusion of a preposition and its complement (such as *downstairs*, from *down (the) stairs*, and *underground*, from *under (the) ground*).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Some words can function both as adverbs and as prepositions, such as *inside*, *aboard*, *underneath* (for instance, one can say "go inside", with adverbial use, or "go inside the house", with prepositional use).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Such cases are analogous to verbs that can be used either transitively or intransitively, and the adverbial forms might therefore be analyzed as "intransitive prepositions".
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] This analysis could also be extended to other adverbs, such as *here* (this place), *there* (that place), *afterward*, etc., even though these never take complements.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Many English phrasal verbs contain particles that are used adverbially, even though they mostly have the form of a preposition (such words may be called prepositional adverbs).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Examples are *on* in *carry on*, *get on*, etc., and *over* in *take over*, *fall over*, and so on.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] The equivalents in Dutch and German are separable prefixes, which also often have the same form as prepositions: for example, Dutch *aanbieden* and German *anbieten* (both meaning "to offer") contain the separable prefix *aan/an*, which is also a preposition meaning "on" or "to".
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] It would be possible to analyze such conjunctions (or even other subordinating conjunctions) as prepositions that take an entire clause as a complement.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In some languages, including a number of Chinese varieties, many of the words that serve as prepositions can also be used as verbs.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Because of this overlap, and the fact that a sequence of prepositional phrases and verb phrases often resembles a serial verb construction, Chinese prepositions (and those of other languages with similar grammatical structures) are often referred to as coverbs.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] As noted in previous sections, Chinese can also be said to have postpositions, although these can be analyzed as nominal (noun) elements.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] For more information, see the article on Chinese grammar, particularly the sections on coverbs and locative phrases.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Some grammatical case markings have a similar function to adpositions; a case affix in one language may be equivalent in meaning to a preposition or postposition in another.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] For example, in English, the agent of a passive construction is marked by the preposition *by*, while in Russian it is marked by the use of the instrumental case.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Sometimes such equivalences exist within a single language; for example, the genitive case in German is often interchangeable with a phrase using the preposition *von* (just as in English, the preposition *of* is often interchangeable with the possessive suffix *'s*).
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Adpositions combine syntactically with their complement, whereas case markings combine with a noun morphologically.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Even so, a clear distinction cannot always be made.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] For example, the post-nominal elements in Japanese and Korean are sometimes called case particles and sometimes postpositions.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] Sometimes they are analyzed as two different groups because they have different characteristics (e.g., the ability to combine with focus particles), but in such analysis, it is unclear which words should fall into which group.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] In these examples, the case markings form a word with their hosts (as shown by vowel harmony, other word-internal effects and agreement of adjectives in Finnish), while the postpositions are independent words.
[src:australian-kriol/adposition] As is seen in the last example, adpositions are often used in conjunction with case affixes – in languages that have a case, a given adposition usually takes a complement in a particular case, and sometimes (as has been seen above) the choice of the case helps specify the meaning of the adposition.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] An **adverb** is a word or an expression that generally modifies a verb, an adjective, another adverb, a determiner, a clause, a preposition, or a sentence.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] Adverbs typically express manner, place, time, frequency, degree, or level of certainty by answering questions such as *how*, *in what way*, *when*, *where*, *to what extent*.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] This is called the adverbial function and may be performed by an individual adverb, by an adverbial phrase, or by an adverbial clause.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] Adverbs are traditionally regarded as one of the parts of speech.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] The English word *adverb* derives (through French) from Latin *adverbium*, from *ad-* ('to'), *verbum* ('word', 'verb'), and the nominal suffix *- ium*.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] The term implies that the principal function of adverbs is to act as modifiers of verbs or verb phrases.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] An adverb used in this way may provide information about the manner, place, time, frequency, certainty, or other circumstances of the activity denoted by the verb or verb phrase.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] Adverbs can also be used as modifiers of adjectives, and of other adverbs, often to indicate degree.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] Adverbs thus perform a wide range of modifying functions.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] The major exception is the function of modifier of nouns, which is performed instead by adjectives (compare *she sang loudly* with *her loud singing disturbed me*; here the verb *sang* is modified by the adverb *loudly*, whereas the noun *singing* is modified by the adjective *loud*).
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] The word *even* in the first sentence is an adjective, since it is a prepositive modifier that modifies the noun *numbers*.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] When the function of an adverb is performed by an expression consisting of more than one word, it is called an adverbial phrase or adverbial clause, or simply an adverbial.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] In English, adverbs of manner (answering the question *how?*) are often formed by adding *-ly* to adjectives, but flat adverbs (such as in *drive fast*, *drive slow*, and *drive friendly*) have the same form as the corresponding adjective.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] Many other adverbs, however, are not related to adjectives in this way; they may be derived from other words or phrases, or may be single morphemes.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] Examples of such adverbs in English include *here, there, together, yesterday, aboard, very, almost*, etc.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] Where the meaning permits, adverbs may undergo comparison, taking comparative and superlative forms.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] In English this is usually done by adding *more* and *most* before the adverb (*more slowly, most slowly*), although there are a few adverbs that take inflected forms, such as *well*, for which *better* and *best* are used.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] For more information about the formation and use of adverbs in English, see English adverbs.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] For other languages, see § In other languages below, and the articles on individual languages and their grammars.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] Adverbs are considered a part of speech in traditional English grammar, and are still included as a part of speech in grammar taught in schools and used in dictionaries.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] However, modern grammarians recognize that words traditionally grouped together as adverbs serve a number of different functions.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] Some describe adverbs as a "catch-all" category that includes all words that do not belong to one of the other parts of speech.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] A logical approach to dividing words into classes relies on recognizing which words can be used in a certain context.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] When this approach is taken, it is seen that adverbs fall into a number of different categories.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] For example, some adverbs can be used to modify an entire sentence, whereas others cannot.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] Even when a sentential adverb has other functions, the meaning is often not the same.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] Words like *very* afford another example.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] *Perry is very fast* is grammatical, but not *Perry very won the race*.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] These words can modify adjectives but not verbs.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] On the other hand, there are words like *here* and *there* that cannot modify adjectives.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] *The sock looks good there* is grammatical, but not *It is a there beautiful sock*.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] The fact that many adverbs can be used in more than one of these functions can confuse the issue, and it may seem like splitting hairs to say that a single adverb is really two or more words that serve different functions.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] However, this distinction can be useful, especially when considering adverbs like *naturally* that have different meanings in their different functions.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] Rodney Huddleston distinguishes between a *word* and a *lexicogrammatical-word*.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] Grammarians find difficulty categorizing negating words, such as the English *not*.
[src:australian-kriol/adverb] Although traditionally listed as an adverb, this word does not behave grammatically like any other, and it probably should be placed in a class of its own.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Despite its similarities to English in vocabulary, it has a distinct syntactic structure and grammar.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] It is a language in its own right and is distinct from Torres Strait Creole.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] The first records of the progenitor to Kriol, a pidgin called Port Jackson Pidgin English (PJPE), are found from the 1780s, with the pidgin being used for communication between the white settlers around Port Jackson and the local indigenous population.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] During that period, relations between the native Australians and Europeans were strained and often violent.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Aboriginal people fiercely defended their lands.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] However, the control of lands was eventually seized by the settlers when a cattle company acquired much of the area.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] The settlers became more determined to take full control of the land from the native people and carried out a campaign to do so.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] European settlement in the Northern Territory was attempted over a period of about forty years.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Settlement finally succeeded in 1870 with the founding of Darwin, and an influx of English and Chinese speakers followed.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] To communicate between these two groups and the local Aboriginal people, many pidgins developed throughout the territory based on PJPE.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] By 1900, PJPE had developed into Northern Territory Pidgin English (NTPE), which was widespread and well understood.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Then, by 1908, NTPE would creolise into Australian Kriol, starting first in the Roper River Mission.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] One reason for this was the resettlements and land seizures that nearly annihilated the indigenous population, as they created drastic social change.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Another reason was that the Anglican mission had between 70–200 people at any given times from eight different aboriginal ethnic groups who spoke different native languages.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Although adult members of these groups were multilingual because of frequent meetings and ceremonies, the children communicated almost entirely in NTPE, except for close friends and family with whom they would have shared a home language.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] But NTPE would not have been sufficient for communication so the children naturally expanded the pidgin until it creolised into Australian Kriol.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Children from these communities disseminated English features throughout their communities.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Although the relations between the missionaries and Aboriginal people were friendly, the missionaries were not responsible for the development of Kriol.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] In fact, they tried to introduce Standard English as the official language for the mission, which the Aboriginal children used in class and with the missionaries, but Kriol still flourished.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Not all speakers of NTPE would switch over to Australian Kriol though as many after 1908 continued to speak NTPE.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Kriol gradually spread and this spread was significantly sped up by policy changes made after World War 2 as well as changes caused directly by World War 2.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] This process of creolisation entailed a massive increase in the lexicon as well as a complexification of the grammar of the language.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] When NTPE speaking communities creolised not all NTPE speakers would start speaking Kriol for those in more peripheral parts of the Kriol speaking area their NTPE was heavily influenced by English so when it creolised it became a dialect of Australian Aboriginal English heavily influenced by Kriol.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Kriol was not recognised as a language until the 1970s, as it was regarded as a dialect of English.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] A Kriol orthography began development in 1973, shortly after the Australian Government's announcement of an education policy using English, Kriol, and Aboriginal languages.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Though a small amount of work had been done in 1967 by Mary Harris and Margaret Sharpe, their work had not been built on, and Kriol orthography has little influence from their work.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] From 1973 to 1975 linguists John Sandefur and Sharpe worked on the orthography with only limited involvement from native speakers of Kriol.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] By mid 1976 Kriol speakers from a Ngukurr school had become involved in the project, ensuring the orthography would work for both the Bamyili and Ngukurr dialects, as at the time these two dialects were the most known amongst the wider Australian establishment.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] By November 1976 the orthography was complete and was launched with a four-week Kriol writers' course in Bamyili and Ngukurr schools.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] In her first speech in April 2013, Josie Farrer spoke in Kriol and Gija, marking the first ever use of an indigenous language in the Western Australian Parliament.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] The Kriol language, unlike many other Aboriginal languages, remains healthy, with most of its speakers under 30 years old.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] About 99% of Kriol speakers are Australian Aboriginals, while only 0.8% belong to other groups, indicating that Kriol functions primarily as an in-group language.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] While Kriol is predominantly spoken rather than written, with generally low literacy rates among its speakers, various organisations and initiatives are working to promote Kriol literacy and media presence through education, original content creation and translations of existing works.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Views on the Kriol language vary widely.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Some dispute its status as a distinct language, dismissing it as either English or poorly spoken English.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Others see it as a threat to traditional Aboriginal languages, while many embrace and actively support it.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Government support remains limited, with only two bilingual programs ever established; those being in Barunga and Ngukurr.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Although the Barunga program has since closed, both programs successfully incorporated Kriol as both a teaching medium and a subject of study.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Code switching between Kriol and English, as well as between Light and Heavy Kriol, is common practice.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Light Kriol and English are typically used in formal settings, while Heavy Kriol is preferred among Aboriginal people and in casual situations, similar to how speakers switch between formal and informal English.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] In areas bordering Kriol-speaking regions, a process of decreolisation has occurred, with speakers shifting toward Australian Aboriginal English while retaining some Kriol features.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] This trend is most noticeable among mixed-race Aboriginal Australians living in larger towns with significant European populations.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Historically, widespread discrimination led many to suppress their Aboriginal heritage and view Kriol as incorrect English that needed to be eliminated.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] These factors, combined with constant exposure to English, led to a gradual language shift.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] While racism has diminished, continued contact with English means that in some communities, although the Aboriginal population can speak Kriol, Aboriginal English remains the primary language for interaction with European-descent Australians and others.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Another form of decreolisation occurs when early Kriol speakers relocate to areas where Kriol is not used.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Without regular exposure to Kriol and surrounded by English speakers, their language would shift toward English.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] However, the extent of decreolisation poses no significant threat to Kriol.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] With a high birthrate among Kriol speakers and decreolisation affecting only a small minority in approximately 6 out of 250 Kriol-speaking communities, the language maintains its vitality.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Kriol exists along a post-creole continuum, with dialects ranging from those closer to Australian Aboriginal English to those more distinct from it.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Heavy Kriol, which differs more substantially from English, incorporates more words from Australian Aboriginal languages and features more divergent word order and phonology.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Light Kriol, on the other hand, maintains more English-like characteristics, including English suffixes, similar phonology and a higher proportion of English vocabulary.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Between these two extremes lies a spectrum of mesolects, representing varying degrees of difference from standard English.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] The choice between Light and Heavy Kriol often reflects speakers' level of integration into mainstream Anglo-Australian society.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Indigenous Australians who are more integrated into broader society typically use Light Kriol, while those who maintain stronger traditional ties and often speak an Indigenous Australian language as their first language tend to use Heavy Kriol.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Mutual intelligibility between Kriol and English is limited, though it varies depending on the dialect.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] While Light Kriol is more comprehensible to English speakers than Heavy Kriol, even then understanding is superficial.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] English speakers may grasp the general meaning of Kriol speech but struggle to understand specific details.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Aside from this acrolectic spectrum, Australian Kriol encompasses several geographic dialects, organised in a hierarchy of regional and local variations.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Major regional dialects are centred around Roper River, Barunga, Fitzroy Valley, Halls Creek, Daly River, Belyuen, Turkey Creek-Wyndham-Kununurra area and the Barkly Tableland, with possible distinct dialects around the Victoria River.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Each regional dialect further subdivides into local dialects, typically associated with individual settlements, though these smaller variations remain largely unstudied.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] These dialects differ in their phonology, grammar and lexicon.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] A general pattern emerges: dialects in more populated, accessible areas tend toward Light Kriol, showing stronger English influence, while those in more isolated, less populated regions typically align with Heavy Kriol.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Each dialect community usually descends from speakers of a particular Indigenous language, leading to the incorporation of vocabulary from that language.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] While speakers of other dialects can understand these distinct vocabulary items, they typically do not use them themselves.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Among these geographic variations, the dialects of the Roper River and Barunga regions have received the most thorough documentation and study.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Australian Kriol also exhibits social dialects or sociolects.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] One notable variety is *strit tok* (street talk), a youth slang often criticised by traditional speakers as a corruption of "proper" Kriol.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Another variant is Borunga Kriol, spoken by non-native Kriol speakers attempting to communicate with Kriol speakers.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Borunga Kriol speakers fall into two groups: language learners who produce an "English-Kriol interlanguage" while acquiring the language, and those who intentionally speak a simplified, incorrect version of English in an attempt to mimic Kriol.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] This latter form, known as "Mock Kriol", bears little resemblance to authentic Kriol and represents an inaccurate imitation of the language.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Two distinct creole languages have also emerged from contact between Kriol and other Aboriginal languages.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Gurndji Creole developed in the Victoria River District through extensive code-switching between Kriol and Gurindji.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Similarly, Light Warlpiri emerged in the town of Lajamanu through rapid code-switching between Kriol, English and Warlpiri.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Australian Kriol is influenced by the phonologies of various Indigenous Australian languages, resulting in individual phonological variation based on the Indigenous languages of its speakers.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Australian Kriol phonotactics dictates that consonant clusters at the start of words must be a plosive followed by a liquid, rhotic or glide consonant, the only exception is an alveolar fricative followed by a plosive.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Consonant clusters at the end of words are nonexistent except for the clusters /lb/ and /ks/.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] The Kriol alphabet is based on the English alphabet, but varies not only in what letters and digraphs are used, but also in the rules for said letters and digraphs.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Each phoneme in Kriol can only be spelled one way, unlike in English orthography, where several different spellings can be used to make the same sound.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Kriol, unlike English, also uses a phonetic orthography in which words are spelled to match how they sound.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] The Kriol alphabet contains 21 letters, 11 consonant digraphs, 5 vowel digraphs and 5 punctuation marks.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] As a general rule, the grammar of Kriol is a simplified version of that found in English, meaning that it is analytic, with words generally having only one form and additional meaning derived not from changing words but from word order and added new words.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] The parts of speech which Australian Kriol has are: verbs, modals, tense markers, adverbs, nouns, pronouns, adjectives, demonstratives, quantifiers, articles, plural markers, prepositions, and particles.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Kriol pronouns differentiate between different between first, second and third person, as well as between singular, plural, and dual plural inclusive and exclusive pronouns first person.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] The language also differentiates between subject, object, independent pronoun, and adnominal possessive.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] There are also reflexive and reciprocal pronouns.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Various types of words in Kriol have one or more suffixes associated with them with certain suffixes being used for several different types of words.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] In Australian Kriol, many spatial words from English have been transformed into suffixes attached to verbs they interact with.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] The specific suffixes vary between dialects but remain mostly similar.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Kriol uses an SVO word order exclusively.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] In Kriol the order of possessor and possessum varies, with it being evenly split between possessor possessum and possessum possessor.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] In Kriol word order is evenly split between verb object adverb and Adverb verb object.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Word order is used over inflections or subject object affixation or verbs to specify meaning.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] In Kriol, reduplication can be used both on the root of a verb and on the entire verb to make the verb a progressive verb.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] There are a significant number of loanwords from Australian Aboriginal languages in Australian Kriol.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] These words most frequently come from semantic domains which were of particular significance to Aboriginal Australians such as kinship, ceremony and nature or were primarily discussed among the family and language group such as familial terms.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Examples of these include the words *lambarra* (father in law), *corroboree* (sacred dance) and *jaojao* (water lily stalk).
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] New words have often been coined to fill lexical gaps instead of borrowing from Aboriginal languages.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Words were also sometimes semantically changed or expanded to fill new meanings.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Many famous pieces of media such Shakespeare and Waltzing Matilda have been translated into Kriol, and many books have been published in Kriol.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] ABC and several other organizations currently make news in Kriol.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Online there are several videos and texts available in Kriol, as well as resources for learning the language.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] There is also an Australian Kriol Wikipedia currently on the Wikimedia Incubator.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] On 5 May 2007, the first complete edition of the Bible in the Kriol language was launched at Katherine in the Northern Territory.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] It was undertaken by a team of native Kriol speakers led by Rev.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] Canon Gumbuli Wurrumara and specialists from the Society for Australian Indigenous Languages.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] The Kriol Bible is the first complete edition of the Bible in any Indigenous Australian language.
[src:australian-kriol/australian-kriol] The publication was a joint venture of The Bible Society, Lutheran Bible Translators, The Church Missionary Society, the Anglican church, Wycliffe Bible Translators, and the Australian Society of Indigenous Languages.
